SIMPLE: spawl
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spawl
<hw>Spawl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A splinter or fragment,
as of wood or stone. See <er>Spall</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spawl</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spawl
<hw>Spawl</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. AS. <ets>sp⟦amac⟧tl</ets>, fr.
<ets>sp⟦aemac⟧tan</ets> to spit; probably akin to
<ets>sp⟦imac⟧wan</ets>, E. <ets>spew</ets>. Cf. <er>Spew</er>.]</ety>
<def>Scattered or ejected spittle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spawl</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Spawl
<hw>Spawl</hw>, <pos>v. i. & t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Spawled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Spawling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. AS.
<ets>sp⟦amac⟧tlian</ets>.]</ety> <def>To scatter spittle from the mouth;
to spit, as saliva.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why must he sputter, <qex>spawl</qex>, and slaver it⟦br⟧
In vain, against the people's favorite.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spawling</ent>⟦br⟧
